<h2 id="goal">Goal</h2>

<p>I‚Äôll never forget the overwhelming feeling when I first started learning web development. There were terms I‚Äôd never heard of, multiple programming languages, front-end development, back-end development, and web frameworks.</p>

<p>Learning how each of these various pieces fit together wasn‚Äôt easy and there was always the fear that I‚Äôd be wasting my time learning something I didn‚Äôt need to learn.</p>

<p>In this tutorial we‚Äôre going to clarify web development terms such as HTML, CSS, JavaScript, server-side programming, client-side programming, databases, JSON, and so on to give you a grasp of how everything fits together at a high level.</p>

<div class="box">
  <p>Got an idea for a tutorial? Contact me <a href="https://twitter.com/atommorgan" target="_blank">on Twitter</a> and I might publish it on this blog!</p>
</div>

<h2 id="how-does-the-web-work">How does the web work?</h2>

<p>First we need to start with how the web works.</p>

<p>Let‚Äôs think about a site like Twitter. When you access someone‚Äôs Twitter account, let‚Äôs use @realDonaldTrump as an example, the main content you see is a feed of tweets from Donald Trump. You see a feed of Trump‚Äôs tweets by accessing his Twitter URL: <a href="https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump" target="_blank">https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump</a>.</p>

<p>When you enter this URL into the browser you‚Äôve made what‚Äôs known as an HTTP request to Twitter‚Äôs servers. That HTTP request is then received by Twitter and it‚Äôs their job to handle this request. In this case Twitter sees you‚Äôre trying to access @realDonaldTrump‚Äôs account so they query their database to get any of @realDonaldTrump‚Äôs data that is needed to view this page such as his name, tweets, following count, follower count, and any other information that‚Äôs used to populate his page.</p>

<p>Once Twitter finishes querying their database for this information, they respond to the browser‚Äôs request (the one you originally made when you entered in the URL <a href="https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump" target="_blank">https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump</a>) by sending back the data from their database.</p>

<div class="box">
  <p>If you‚Äôve ever seen or heard the term <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/JSON">JSON</a>, that‚Äôs the file format that‚Äôs typically used to send this data but more on that in a later tutorial.</p>
</div>

<p>Once this data is received by the browser, the HTML page you see in the browser is then constructed using the data sent back from Twitter.</p>

<p><img src="/images/what-is-web-dev/trump-twitter.png" alt="Trump's Twitter" /></p>

<h2 id="client-server-model">Client server model</h2>

<p>This model‚Äîmaking a request to a site like Twitter and receiving data in response‚Äîis what‚Äôs known as a client-server model. We can see the previous example illustrated in the following image where the client is a web browser and the server is Twitter.</p>

<div class="box">
  <p>We use the term ‚Äúclient‚Äù here instead of something like ‚Äúcomputer‚Äù to be a bit more general because the number of devices that can act as clients continues to grow. You can now access Twitter from your laptop, tablet, smartphone, TV, video game consoles, etc. All of these would classify as a ‚Äúclient‚Äù in the client-server model.</p>
</div>

<p><img src="/images/what-is-web-dev/client-server-user.png" alt="Client-Server User POV" /></p>

<p>This shows a client-server model at a nearly technology agnostic level. We haven‚Äôt even talked programming languages or back-end vs front-end yet. So considering that all of these are used to make web applications such as Twitter, how do they fit in to this client-server model?</p>

<p><img src="/images/what-is-web-dev/client-server-dev.png" alt="Client-Server Developer POV" /></p>

<p>As you can see our previous labels for ‚ÄúBrowser‚Äù and ‚ÄúTwitter‚Äù have been replaced with some underlying technologies that are used such as ‚ÄúReact‚Äù and ‚ÄúNode.js‚Äù. This is where some of the various frameworks you may have heard of start to come in.</p>

<p>In this hypothetical example, Twitter‚Äôs front-end application is built using React. This React application makes requests to a Node.js back-end that uses a MongoDB database to store any data.</p>

<h2 id="front-end-vs-back-end">Front end vs. back end</h2>

<p>Any code that‚Äôs running on a browser is ‚Äúfront-end‚Äù code using frameworks such as React, Angular, Vue.js, or Ember. Front-end developers write code that‚Äôs executed on a client, such as a web browser. It displays a web page to the user using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript.</p>

<p>Any code that‚Äôs running on a server is ‚Äúback-end‚Äù code using frameworks such as Ruby on Rails, Node.js, Laravel, or Django. Back-end developers write code that‚Äôs executed on a server responding to requests made by clients. Back-end developers will also work with a database if necessary to fulfill those requests.</p>

<p>The distinction between front-end and back-end is delineated by the client that‚Äôs <strong><em>making the request</em></strong> and the server that‚Äôs sending a <strong><em>response to the request</em></strong> back to the client.</p>

<p>Front-end is what you see, back-end is what you don‚Äôt see.</p>

